<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7462</anchor> <rss>jms-00IC.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IC</addr>  <route>jms-00IC.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> for program equivalence</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>e,e'</tex> be two programs of type <tex>\tau</tex>. We say that <tex>e</tex> and <tex>e'</tex> are <em><strong>observationally equivalent</strong></em> when for any other program <tex>h \colon   \tau   \to   { \mathopen {} \left ( \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>, then <tex>h { \mathopen {} \left ( e \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> terminates if and only if <tex>h { \mathopen {} \left ( e' \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> terminates. If <tex>E_ \tau</tex> is the set of programs of type <tex>\tau</tex>, observational equivalence therefore forms a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>E_ \tau \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  E_ \tau</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7463</anchor> <rss>jms-00I8.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00I8</addr>  <route>jms-00I8.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Uses of <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link> in computer science</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7464</anchor> <rss>jms-00I9.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00I9</addr>  <route>jms-00I9.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> in program specification</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>In the simplest terms, a specification of a program is a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> that describes the possible input/output pairs that can occur. For example, the specification that a given program compute the square root is captured by the <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>\mathsf {sq}  \colon   \mathbb {R}_{ \geq  0}  \mathbin { \nrightarrow }   \mathbb {R}</tex> given by pairs <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( x,y \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> such that <tex>x = y^2</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7465</anchor> <rss>jms-00IA.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IA</addr>  <route>jms-00IA.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> in operational semantics</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>E</tex> represent the set of states in a machine; then the behavior of this machine is usually described by a pair of <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link> <tex>S  \colon  E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  E</tex> and <tex>V \colon  E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }   { \mathopen {} \left \{ \star \right \} \mathclose {}}</tex>, such that <tex>e \mathrel {S} e'</tex> when it is possible for the machine to transition from state <tex>e</tex> to <tex>e'</tex> and such that <tex>e \mathrel {V}  \star</tex> when the machine can halt in state <tex>e</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7466</anchor> <rss>jms-00IB.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IB</addr>  <route>jms-00IB.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> in program typing</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>E</tex> be the set of expression in a given programming language, and let <tex>T</tex> be the set of types in that programming language. Then the property of a given program having a certain type forms a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  T</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7467</anchor> <rss>jms-00IC.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IC</addr>  <route>jms-00IC.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> for program equivalence</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>e,e'</tex> be two programs of type <tex>\tau</tex>. We say that <tex>e</tex> and <tex>e'</tex> are <em><strong>observationally equivalent</strong></em> when for any other program <tex>h \colon   \tau   \to   { \mathopen {} \left ( \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>, then <tex>h { \mathopen {} \left ( e \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> terminates if and only if <tex>h { \mathopen {} \left ( e' \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> terminates. If <tex>E_ \tau</tex> is the set of programs of type <tex>\tau</tex>, observational equivalence therefore forms a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>E_ \tau \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  E_ \tau</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7468</anchor> <rss>jms-00ID.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00ID</addr>  <route>jms-00ID.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Networks as <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link></title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em><strong>network</strong></em> is given by a set of nodes <tex>N</tex> and a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>C \colon  N \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  N</tex> expressing with two nodes are connected.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7469</anchor> <rss>jms-00IE.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IE</addr>  <route>jms-00IE.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title><link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">Relations</link> in databases</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We now come to an example of a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation between multiple sets</link>: we could define a relation <tex>R \subseteq   \text {Movies} \times \text {Directors} \times \text {Years} \times \text {People}</tex> consisting of tuples <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( m,d,y,p \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> where <tex>m</tex> is a movie directed by <tex>d</tex> in year <tex>y</tex> with <tex>p</tex> as a cast member.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7470</anchor> <rss>jms-00I7.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00I7</addr>  <route>jms-00I7.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Relation</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em><strong>(binary) relation</strong></em> <tex>R</tex> from a set <tex>A</tex> to a set <tex>B</tex>, written <tex>R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex> or <tex>R \in   \mathrm {Rel} { \mathopen {} \left ( A,B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> is defined to be a subset <tex>R \subseteq  A \times  B</tex>. We shall typically write <tex>a \mathrel {R}b</tex> for <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( a,b \right ) \mathclose {}} \in  R</tex>. More generally, a <em><strong>relation between multiple sets</strong></em> <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A_i \right ) \mathclose {}} _{i \in  I}</tex> is defined to be a subset of the cartesian product <tex>\prod _{i \in  I} A_i</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>